    <stitle>ALTERNATOR: DELCO-REMY 30-SI AND 30-SI/TR SERIES - OPERATION - 30-SI/TR SERIES</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="operate" graphiccount="3">
        <title>30-SI/TR SERIES</title>
        <para>The basic 30-SI/TR charging system is shown in
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0801608">Figure 8</hotlnk>. For actual wiring schematic, refer to the appropriate vehicle
            circuit diagram in the Service Manual.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0801608" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0801608" filename="../figg08/G0801608.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Typical 30-SI/TR Charging System</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. 12/24 VOLT ALTERNATOR</callout1>
                <callout1>2. "C" (CRANKING) BATTERY</callout1>
                <callout1>3. START SWITCH</callout1>
                <callout1>4. MAGNETIC SWITCH</callout1>
                <callout1>5. VEHICLE ELECTRICAL LOADS</callout1>
                <callout1>6. "S" (SYSTEM) BATTERY</callout1>
                <callout1>7. CRANKING MOTOR (24 VOLT)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>The 30-SI and system or "S" battery, operate together in the normal manner in the 12-volt vehicle
            electrical system. The transformer rectifier, or TR unit, is an "add on" unit on the 30-SI generator. It
            charges the cranking or "C" battery which is connected in series with "S" battery to provide 24 volts to the
            cranking motor. When the engine is running, the "C" battery "floats on the line" and receives a low charge
            rate from the TR unit to maintain its full state of charge.
        </para>
        <para>
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0801609">Figure 9</hotlnk>
            and
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0801610">Figure 10</hotlnk>
            illustrate the wiring circuits for the 30-SI/TR charging system.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0801609" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0801609" filename="../figg08/G0801609.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Wiring Diagram (30-SI/TR) Negative Ground - With Voltage Adjustment</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. VOLTAGE ADJUSTMENT</callout1>
                <callout1>2. STATOR</callout1>
                <callout1>3. TRANSFORMER</callout1>
                <callout1>4. TR BRIDGE</callout1>
                <callout1>5. "C" (CRANKING) BATTERY</callout1>
                <callout1>6. START SWITCH</callout1>
                <callout1>7. MAGNETIC SWITCH</callout1>
                <callout1>8. CRANKING MOTOR (24 VOLT)</callout1>
                <callout1>9. "S" (SYSTEM) BATTERY</callout1>
                <callout1>10. DIODE TRIO</callout1>
                <callout1>11. FIELD COIL</callout1>
                <callout1>12. RECTIFIER BRIDGE</callout1>
                <callout1>13. REGULATOR</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f0801610" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0801610" filename="../figg08/G0801610.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Wiring Diagram (30-SI/TR) Negative Ground-Without Voltage Adjustment</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. STATOR</callout1>
                <callout1>2. TRANSFORMER</callout1>
                <callout1>3. TR BRIDGE</callout1>
                <callout1>4. "C" (CRANKING) BATTERY</callout1>
                <callout1>5. START SWITCH</callout1>
                <callout1>6. MAGNETIC SWITCH</callout1>
                <callout1>7. CRANKING MOTOR (24 VOLT)</callout1>
                <callout1>8. "S" (SYSTEM) BATTERY</callout1>
                <callout1>9. DIODE TRIO</callout1>
                <callout1>10. FIELD COIL</callout1>
                <callout1>11. RECTIFIER BRIDGE</callout1>
                <callout1>12. REGULATOR</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>The lower portion of the circuit, with the system or "S" battery is the same as the 30-SI circuit shown in
            <hotlnk document="s08016_2.xml" xrefid="f0801606">Figure 6</hotlnk>and
            <hotlnk document="s08016_2.xml" xrefid="f0801607">Figure 7</hotlnk>and operates in the same manner.
        </para>
        <para>A transformer-rectifier, or TR unit, is mounted on the rectifier end frame, and is connected to the
            cranking, or "C" battery, as shown. The two batteries are connected in series to provide 24 volts for
            cranking or starting.
        </para>
        <para>The delta primary of the transformer is connected to the delta stator. The AC voltages in the stator cause
            an AC current to flow in the primary. This changing, or AC current, creates magnetic fields which induce
            voltages in the transformer secondary winding. The secondary then provides current through the rectifier
            bridge to charge the "C" battery.
        </para>
